@title Pilot Plus Ground Control
@sigils [🛰/塔]
@audience peripheral designers, agent architects, multi-agent operators
@tone foundational
@style pattern
@keywords peripheral, pilot, ground-control, inhabitation, separation-of-powers, live-fix, supervised-autonomy, consent-gate, instrument, envelope
@references [peripherals/constrained-execution-envelope peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution orchestration/consent-gate coordination/capability-gate realtime/learn-as-you-go]

! conclusion: When an agent inhabits a powerful peripheral whose instrument is itself under repair, split the work into two roles — a PILOT who flies strictly inside the envelope by the instrument's readings, and a GROUND CONTROL who stays outside it, owns the substrate, source-checks the pilot's observations, and fixes the instrument live. Neither role works alone; the pattern is the pair.

  + context: A peripheral (in the constrained-execution-envelope sense) gives
    an agent real leverage: a War Machine pilot REPL, a proof cockpit, a
    deploy console. But the instrument behind the envelope — the scorer, the
    scanner, the registry it reads — is imperfect and under active
    development. You want the flying to happen AND the instrument to get
    fixed, without either corrupting the other.

  + IF:
    An agent can inhabit the peripheral and work it productively, and a
    second agent has the access and context to repair the substrate the
    peripheral reads from (live code reload, registries, scoring models).

  + HOWEVER:
    One agent cannot honestly do both jobs. The inhabitant who hits an
    instrument defect faces a bad fork: break the envelope to go fix the
    substrate (abandoning the flight discipline that makes the readings
    meaningful), or keep flying a broken instrument (laundering bad readings
    into apparently-earned outcomes). And an agent that authors its own
    instrument fixes mid-flight reviews nothing — author and reviewer
    collapse into one seat exactly where the stakes are highest.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Role bleed: the pilot starts patching the substrate, or ground
        control starts flying cycles. Both losses are silent — the envelope
        discipline and the review gate each look intact while meaning
        nothing.
      - Diagnosis trust: ground control fixes what the pilot DIAGNOSED
        instead of what the pilot OBSERVED. Pilots misread root causes
        routinely (it is not their instrument to open); the contract is
        observations cross the boundary, diagnoses do not.
      - Double dispatch: both roles hand work to the same builder pool and
        the same fix gets built twice. Needs an explicit lane convention
        (e.g. single-dispatch-per-kind: builds via pilot, substrate fixes
        via ground control) or a mutual-ack handshake.
      - Stale-state crossings: the two roles exchange findings
        asynchronously; each acts on the other's old state. Mitigations:
        low-latency agent processes, per-recipient FIFO delivery, sequence
        or as-of fields in the message envelope, and the habit of
        re-reading live state before acting on a report.
      - Ground-control paternalism: overriding the pilot's warranted
        choices instead of source-checking them. Ground control checks the
        instrument, not the pilot's judgment; the operator, not ground
        control, decides strategy.

  + THEN:
    Split the work into two named roles with a hard boundary at the
    envelope's edge.

    The PILOT inhabits the peripheral and flies strictly by its readings
    and its disciplines: consent gates before anything outward, earned
    closure (no discharge claimed that the field did not actually yield),
    target checks before executing a recommendation, and a turn log that
    records predicted versus realised. When the instrument looks wrong, the
    pilot HOLDS and reports the observation — staying in the seat.

    GROUND CONTROL stays outside the envelope and owns everything the
    envelope reads: source-checks each pilot observation against the actual
    code before accepting the pilot's framing; fixes the substrate live
    (hot reload, never restarting the world under the pilot); gates any
    built artifact (read the diff, re-run the verification, state what was
    checked); and relays genuinely strategic decisions upward to the
    operator instead of absorbing them.

    Findings flow pilot → ground control as observations. Fixes flow
    ground control → substrate, with the pilot re-reading the field to
    confirm each fix moved it. Strategy flows operator → both, through
    consent gates that the apparatus surfaces rather than bypasses.

  + BECAUSE:
    The envelope boundary is exactly where the two kinds of integrity live.
    The pilot's readings are only evidence if the flight discipline holds —
    a pilot who also mutates the instrument mid-reading destroys the
    interpretability of their own log. Ground control's fixes are only
    trustworthy if made from outside — with the full substrate in view,
    against source, under review gates the pilot cannot see from the
    cockpit. Separation of powers here is not bureaucracy; it is what makes
    either role's output mean anything.

    And the pair error-corrects in both directions. The pilot's discipline
    catches what the instrument misses (a confidently-scored impossible
    action). Ground control's source-check catches what the pilot misreads
    (a plausible wrong root cause). The operator's consent gate catches
    what both miss (a mechanically-valid move that is strategically wrong).
    Three layers, each covering the others' blind spots — the same shape as
    measure-never-target and the other anti-laundering disciplines: no
    layer certifies itself.

    + evidence: WM pilot go-live, 2026-06-10 (claude-3 pilot, fable-1
      ground control, Joe operator). Two supervised observer cycles, zero
      unilateral mutations, and the pair found and fixed: a forward model
      scoring the spawn of already-existing missions (pilot's earned-closure
      discipline caught the WM's own #1 recommendation as an un-earnable
      teleport; ground control traced it to predict-effects and converted
      the action class); a multi-watcher wedge fixed live mid-flight without
      disturbing the pilot; a sorry registry that had been silently empty
      for 16 days (refilled with five provenance-checked holes, after which
      the field's top five recommendations became the system's own
      gate-clearing work); and a calibration harness whose first honest
      verdict was that no admissible evidence existed yet. Both directions
      of error-correction fired: the pilot mis-diagnosed twice
      (stale-judgement, scope-tree staleness) and ground control's
      source-check corrected both; ground control misread once (a
      timezone comparison) and said so, which surfaced an untimed
      subprocess wait as a bonus. The operator's consent gate converted a
      mechanically-valid "advance" into the strategic question it really
      was (start a new workstream?), answered at a higher level than asked.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Name the roles explicitly at session start; record the dispatch
      lanes (who hands work to builders, who touches the substrate).
    - Give the pilot a HOLD verb and a discipline that makes holding
      reportable as success, not failure — the most valuable cycle of the
      validation run was one where nothing executed.
    - Give ground control a review-gate liturgy: read the diff, re-run the
      verification, state what was checked, fix small findings yourself.
    - Put the operator's consent gates in the apparatus (surfaced,
      fillable), not in the conversation.
    - Instrument the boundary: out-of-band events (held actions, refused
      teleports, operator declines) go into a typed channel, because they
      are the highest-gradient learning signal the pair produces.
